<font color="#FF0000">JUST SOME MORE THOUGHTS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct 30 23:45:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
To all,<br><br>
Ed, I needed to take a little time to think about this thread.  My thoughts have changed so much over the years.  The stimuli were familiar when I first came home  I hit the snow when a screen door &quot;slammed&quot; a day after returning home.  Helicopters didn't help.  The song TIME HAS COME TODAY put me in another place and I played it over and over again.  I had dreams and had a hard time sleeping.  I'm sure the stories are familiar.  I &quot;buried&quot; it for awhile roaming around the country.  It came out in spurts that I didn't/couldn't relate to at the time.<br><br>
I got married for the first time in &quot;76.&quot;  When the first marriage started to come apart  (81) &quot;feelings&quot; of abandonment and loss of hope struck hard and I starting going to a rap group and that helped me to start to get a grasp on the meanings behind my feelings.<br><br>
Now, I look at it differently.  I, no longer, separate Vietnam from the rest of my life' s experiences.  I wrote on another thread that I don't believe that Vietnam was any different (absurd) than the rest of life, only that it is more deadly.<br><br>
Death is always hard -- divorce is death -- abandonment in whatever form it takes is death.  I'm sure we can all relate to experiences of &quot;death.&quot;<br><br>
Today I read on this site Anne's comments on thread #122 and Beth and Sherri's comments on thread #4.  It woud be easier for me today to enter another tunnel or walk point in the Hobo Woods today than to experience triage or to be the wife of a vet who lost his smile and didn't know how to regain his old self.  I will try to answer those threads later.  I think many of us would all do better if we took a second or third look at what the women have written on these threads.  They will always be more important than we can imagine.  I'm sure that Cook's wife and five daughters help to keep him &quot;off line&quot; and &quot;in line.&quot;<br><br>
I'm not sure if I am trying to write a treatise on the handling of &quot;death, abandonment, the feelings of betrayal, acceptance of the loss of innocence, or whatever other feelings of angst dwell in us.&quot;<br><br>
There are contradictions to all of &quot;this&quot; in me. I know that I don't want to, (even if I could) lose my Vietnam experience. I have learned more wisdom from my experiences in Vietnam than in other parts of my life, and some of the people around me have benefitted from my time in hell, that's a good thing.  When I close my eyes for the last time I want to be able to say good-bye and I did my best -- most of the time.<br><br>
Jane Fonda is different than Joan Baez and David Harris.  The mess of Vietnam primarily occurred because the rules of the world changed in the middle of the &quot;game,&quot; and to me that was good. (that's a longer note.)<br><br>
I'm running out of energy and I have those other posts to write.<br><br>
Paul
